# Gameplay layout: phone vs iPad in landscape

Larger iPhones (Plus, Pro Max) report **regular** horizontal size class in landscape — the same as iPad. `horizontalSizeClass == .compact` is **not** a reliable "iPhone" signal.

## Rules

1. **Landscape detection** — `verticalSizeClass == .compact`
2. **Phone vs pad in landscape** — `UIDevice.current.userInterfaceIdiom` via `GameplayLayout` helpers with `isPad` (unit tests pass `isPad:` explicitly)
3. **Never** branch phone vs pad on `horizontalSizeClass` alone in match/gameplay screens

## Use these helpers

```swift
// ✅ Phone landscape (any horizontal size class on phone idiom)
GameplayLayout.usesLandscapeIPhoneOnlyMatchScoringLayout(...)
GameplayLayout.usesLandscapeIPhoneMatchScoringLayout(...)  // alias

// ✅ iPad landscape
GameplayLayout.usesLandscapeIPadMatchScoringLayout(...)

// ✅ Cricket: pinned top board + full-width pad (phone only)
GameplayLayout.usesCricketLandscapePinnedLayout(...)

// ✅ Cricket: side-by-side (iPad portrait + iPad landscape only)
GameplayLayout.usesCricketSideBySideMatchScoringLayout(...)

// ❌ BAD — treats Pro Max landscape as iPad
verticalSizeClass == .compact && horizontalSizeClass == .compact

// ❌ BAD — treats Pro Max landscape as iPad
verticalSizeClass == .compact && horizontalSizeClass == .regular
```

## Tests

For every new layout predicate, unit-test `(regular, compact, isPad: false)` and `(regular, compact, isPad: true)`.

Landscape UI tests should run on **iPhone Pro Max** (nightly UI workflow) so regular-width phone landscape is exercised.
